# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battery-charger
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:battery-charger/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:battery-charger/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] An **ammeter** (abbreviation of *ampere meter*) is an instrument used to measure the current in a circuit.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Electric currents are measured in amperes (A), hence the name.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] For direct measurement, the ammeter is connected in series with the circuit in which the current is to be measured.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] An ammeter usually has low resistance so that it does not cause a significant voltage drop in the circuit being measured.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Instruments used to measure smaller currents, in the milliampere or microampere range, are designated as *milliammeters* or *microammeters*.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Early ammeters were laboratory instruments that relied on the Earth's magnetic field for operation.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] By the late 19th century, improved instruments were designed which could be mounted in any position and allowed accurate measurements in electric power systems.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] It is generally represented by letter 'A' in a circuit.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The relation between electric current, magnetic fields and physical forces was first noted by Hans Christian Ørsted in 1820, who observed a compass needle was deflected from pointing North when a current flowed in an adjacent wire.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The tangent galvanometer was used to measure currents using this effect, where the restoring force returning the pointer to the zero position was provided by the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] This made these instruments usable only when aligned with the Earth's field.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Sensitivity of the instrument was increased by using additional turns of wire to multiply the effect – the instruments were called "multipliers".
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The word *rheoscope* as a detector of electrical currents was coined by Sir Charles Wheatstone about 1840 but is no longer used to describe electrical instruments.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The word makeup is similar to that of *rheostat* (also coined by Wheatstone) which was a device used to adjust the current in a circuit.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Rheostat is a historical term for a variable resistance, though unlike rheoscope may still be encountered.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Some instruments are *panel meters*, meant to be mounted on some sort of control panel.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Of these, the flat, horizontal or vertical type is often called an *edgewise meter*.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The D'Arsonval galvanometer is a moving coil ammeter.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] It uses magnetic deflection, where current passing through a coil placed in the magnetic field of a permanent magnet causes the coil to move.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The modern form of this instrument was developed by Edward Weston, and uses two spiral springs to provide the restoring force.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The uniform air gap between the iron core and the permanent magnet poles make the deflection of the meter linearly proportional to current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Basic meter movements can have full-scale deflection for currents from about 25 microamperes to 10 milliamperes.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Because the magnetic field is polarised, the meter needle acts in opposite directions for each direction of current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A DC ammeter is thus sensitive to which polarity it is connected in; most are marked with a positive terminal, but some have centre-zero mechanisms and can display currents in either direction.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A moving coil meter indicates the average (mean) of a varying current through it, which is zero for AC.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] For this reason, moving-coil meters are only usable directly for DC, not AC.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] This type of meter movement is extremely common for both ammeters and other meters derived from them, such as voltmeters and ohmmeters.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Moving magnet ammeters operate on essentially the same principle as moving coil, except that the coil is mounted in the meter case, and a permanent magnet moves the needle.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Moving magnet Ammeters are able to carry larger currents than moving coil instruments, often several tens of amperes, because the coil can be made of thicker wire and the current does not have to be carried by the hairsprings.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Indeed, some Ammeters of this type do not have hairsprings at all, instead using a fixed permanent magnet to provide the restoring force.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] An electrodynamic ammeter uses an electromagnet instead of the permanent magnet of the d'Arsonval movement.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] This instrument can respond to both alternating and direct current and also indicates true RMS for AC.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] See wattmeter for an alternative use for this instrument.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Moving iron ammeters use a piece of iron which moves when acted upon by the electromagnetic force of a fixed coil of wire.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The moving-iron meter was invented by Austrian engineer Friedrich Drexler in 1884.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] This type of meter responds to both direct and alternating currents (as opposed to the moving-coil ammeter, which works on direct current only).
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The iron element consists of a moving vane attached to a pointer, and a fixed vane, surrounded by a coil.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] As alternating or direct current flows through the coil and induces a magnetic field in both vanes, the vanes repel each other and the moving vane deflects against the restoring force provided by fine helical springs.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The deflection of a moving iron meter is proportional to the square of the current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Consequently, such meters would normally have a nonlinear scale, but the iron parts are usually modified in shape to make the scale fairly linear over most of its range.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Moving iron instruments indicate the RMS value of any AC waveform applied.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Moving iron ammeters are commonly used to measure current in industrial frequency AC circuits.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In a hot-wire ammeter, a current passes through a wire which expands as it heats.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Although these instruments have slow response time and low accuracy, they were sometimes used in measuring radio-frequency current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] These also measure true RMS for an applied AC.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In much the same way as the analogue ammeter formed the basis for a wide variety of derived meters, including voltmeters, the basic mechanism for a digital meter is a digital voltmeter mechanism, and other types of meter are built around this.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Digital ammeter designs use a shunt resistor to produce a calibrated voltage proportional to the current flowing.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] This voltage is then measured by a digital voltmeter, through use of an analog-to-digital converter (ADC); the digital display is calibrated to display the current through the shunt.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Such instruments are often calibrated to indicate the RMS value for a sine wave only, but many designs will indicate true RMS within limitations of the wave crest factor.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] There is also a range of devices referred to as integrating ammeters.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In these ammeters the current is summed over time, giving as a result the product of current and time; which is proportional to the electrical charge transferred with that current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] These can be used for metering energy (the charge needs to be multiplied by the voltage to give energy) or for estimating the charge of a battery or capacitor.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A picoammeter, or pico ammeter, measures very low electric current, usually from the picoampere range at the lower end to the milliampere range at the upper end.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Picoammeters are used where the current being measured is below the limits of sensitivity of other devices, such as multimeters.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Most picoammeters use a "virtual short" technique and have several different measurement ranges that must be switched between to cover multiple decades of measurement.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Other modern picoammeters use log compression and a "current sink" method that eliminates range switching and associated voltage spikes.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Special design and usage considerations must be observed in order to reduce leakage current which may swamp measurements such as special insulators and driven shields.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Triaxial cable is often used for probe connections.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Ammeters must be connected in series with the circuit to be measured.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] For relatively small currents (up to a few amperes), an ammeter may pass the whole of the circuit current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] For larger direct currents, a shunt resistor carries most of the circuit current and a small, accurately-known fraction of the current passes through the meter movement.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] For alternating current circuits, a current transformer may be used to provide a convenient small current to drive an instrument, such as 1 or 5 amperes, while the primary current to be measured is much larger (up to thousands of amperes).
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The use of a shunt or current transformer also allows convenient location of the indicating meter without the need to run heavy circuit conductors up to the point of observation.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In the case of alternating current, the use of a current transformer also isolates the meter from the high voltage of the primary circuit.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A shunt provides no such isolation for a direct-current ammeter, but where high voltages are used it may be possible to place the ammeter in the "return" side of the circuit which may be at low potential with respect to earth.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Ammeters must not be connected directly across a voltage source since their internal resistance is very low and excess current would flow.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Ammeters are designed for a low voltage drop across their terminals, much less than one volt; the extra circuit losses produced by the ammeter are called its "burden" on the measured circuit(I).
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Ordinary Weston-type meter movements can measure only milliamperes at most, because the springs and practical coils can carry only limited currents.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] To measure larger currents, a resistor called a *shunt* is placed in parallel with the meter.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The resistances of shunts is in the integer to fractional milliohm range.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Nearly all of the current flows through the shunt, and only a small fraction flows through the meter.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] This allows the meter to measure large currents.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Traditionally, the meter used with a shunt has a full-scale deflection (FSD) of 50 mV, so shunts are typically designed to produce a voltage drop of 50 mV when carrying their full rated current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] To make a multi-range ammeter, a selector switch can be used to connect one of a number of shunts across the meter.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] It must be a make-before-break switch to avoid damaging current surges through the meter movement when switching ranges.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A better arrangement is the Ayrton shunt or universal shunt, invented by William E.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Ayrton, which does not require a make-before-break switch.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] It also avoids any inaccuracy because of contact resistance.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In the figure, assuming for example, a movement with a full-scale voltage of 50 mV and desired current ranges of 10 mA, 100 mA, and 1 A, the resistance values would be: R1 = 4.5 ohms, R2 = 0.45 ohm, R3 = 0.05 ohm.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] And if the movement resistance is 1000 ohms, for example, R1 must be adjusted to 4.525 ohms.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Switched shunts are rarely used for currents above 10 amperes.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Zero-center ammeters are used for applications requiring current to be measured with both polarities, common in scientific and industrial equipment.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Zero-center ammeters are also commonly placed in series with a battery.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In this application, the charging of the battery deflects the needle to one side of the scale (commonly, the right side) and the discharging of the battery deflects the needle to the other side.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A special type of zero-center ammeter for testing high currents in cars and trucks has a pivoted bar magnet that moves the pointer, and a fixed bar magnet to keep the pointer centered with no current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] The magnetic field around the wire carrying current to be measured deflects the moving magnet.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Since the ammeter shunt has a very low resistance, mistakenly wiring the ammeter in parallel with a voltage source will cause a short circuit, at best blowing a fuse, possibly damaging the instrument and wiring, and exposing an observer to injury.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In AC circuits, a current transformer can be used to convert the large current in the main circuit into a smaller current more suited to a meter.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Some designs of transformer are able to directly convert the magnetic field around a conductor into a small AC current, typically either 1 A or 5 A at full rated current, that can be easily read by a meter.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In a similar way, accurate AC/DC non-contact ammeters have been constructed using Hall effect magnetic field sensors.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] A portable hand-held clamp-on ammeter is a common tool for maintenance of industrial and commercial electrical equipment, which is temporarily clipped over a wire to measure current.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Some recent types have a parallel pair of magnetically soft probes that are placed on either side of the conductor.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] In particle accelerators and synchrotron light sources, ammeters with extremely high sensitivity, known as **picoammeters**, are used to measure the tiny currents generated by photodiodes and other beam position monitors (BPMs).
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] These instruments typically provide multiple low-noise input channels with femtoampere to microampere sensitivity, enabling real-time determination of the photon beam position and intensity.
[src:battery-charger/ammeter] Such devices are crucial for beam stabilization and feedback systems in facilities like the Advanced Photon Source at Argonne National Laboratory, where custom picoammeters are employed to ensure precise orbit control and improved beamline performance.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The **amplitude** of a periodic variable is a measure of its change in a single period (such as time or spatial period).
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The amplitude of a non-periodic signal is its magnitude compared with a reference value.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] There are various definitions of amplitude (see below), which are all functions of the magnitude of the differences between the variable's extreme values.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] In older texts, the phase of a periodic function is sometimes called the amplitude.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] In audio system measurements, telecommunications and others where the measurand is a signal that swings above and below a reference value but is not sinusoidal, peak amplitude is often used.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] If the reference is zero, this is the maximum absolute value of the signal; if the reference is a mean value (DC component), the peak amplitude is the maximum absolute value of the difference from that reference.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Semi-amplitude means half of the peak-to-peak amplitude.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The majority of scientific literature employs the term *amplitude* or *peak amplitude* to mean semi-amplitude.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] It is the most widely used measure of orbital wobble in astronomy and the measurement of small radial velocity semi-amplitudes of nearby stars is important in the search for exoplanets (see Doppler spectroscopy).
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Root mean square (RMS) amplitude is used especially in electrical engineering: the RMS is defined as the square root of the mean over time of the square of the vertical distance of the graph from the rest state; i.e. the RMS of the AC waveform (with no DC component).
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] For complicated waveforms, especially non-repeating signals like noise, the RMS amplitude is usually used because it is both unambiguous and has physical significance.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] For example, the *average* power transmitted by an acoustic or electromagnetic wave or by an electrical signal is proportional to the square of the RMS amplitude (and not, in general, to the square of the peak amplitude).
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] For alternating current electric power, the universal practice is to specify RMS values of a sinusoidal waveform.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] One property of root mean square voltages and currents is that they produce the same heating effect as a direct current in a given resistance.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The peak-to-peak value is used, for example, when choosing rectifiers for power supplies, or when estimating the maximum voltage that insulation must withstand.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Some common voltmeters are calibrated for RMS amplitude, but respond to the average value of a rectified waveform.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Many digital voltmeters and all moving coil meters are in this category.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The RMS calibration is only correct for a sine wave input since the ratio between peak, average and RMS values is dependent on waveform.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] If the wave shape being measured is greatly different from a sine wave, the relationship between RMS and average value changes.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] True RMS-responding meters were used in radio frequency measurements, where instruments measured the heating effect in a resistor to measure a current.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The advent of microprocessor-controlled meters capable of calculating RMS by sampling the waveform has made true RMS measurement commonplace.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] In telecommunications, *pulse amplitude* is the magnitude of a pulse parameter, such as the voltage level, current level, field intensity, or power level.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Pulse amplitude is measured with respect to a specified reference and therefore should be modified by qualifiers, such as *average*, *instantaneous*, *peak*, or *root-mean-square*.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Pulse amplitude also applies to the amplitude of frequency- and phase-modulated waveform envelopes.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] For symmetric periodic waves, like sine waves, square waves, or triangle waves, *peak amplitude* and *semi amplitude* are the same.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] However, for an asymmetric wave or wave packet (periodic pulses in one direction, for example), the peak amplitude becomes ambiguous.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] In electrical engineering, the usual solution to this ambiguity is to measure the amplitude from a defined reference potential (such as ground or 0 V).
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Strictly speaking, this is no longer amplitude since there is the possibility that a constant (DC component) is included in the measurement.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The units of the amplitude depend on the type of wave, but are always in the same units as the oscillating variable.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] A more general representation of the wave equation is more complex, but the role of amplitude remains analogous to this simple case.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] For waves on a string, or in a medium such as water, the amplitude is a displacement.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The amplitude of sound waves and audio signals (which relates to the volume) conventionally refers to the amplitude of the air pressure in the wave, but sometimes the amplitude of the displacement (movements of the air or the diaphragm of a speaker) is described.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The logarithm of the amplitude squared is usually quoted in dB, so a null amplitude corresponds to −∞ dB.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Loudness is related to amplitude and intensity and is one of the most salient qualities of a sound, although in general sounds it can be recognized independently of amplitude.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] The square of the amplitude is proportional to the intensity of the wave.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] For electromagnetic radiation, the amplitude of a photon corresponds to the changes in the electric field of the wave.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] However, radio signals may be carried by electromagnetic radiation; the intensity of the radiation (amplitude modulation) or the frequency of the radiation (frequency modulation) is oscillated and then the individual oscillations are varied (modulated) to produce the signal.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Amplitude envelope refers to the changes in the amplitude of a sound over time, and is an influential property as it affects perception of timbre.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] A flat tone has a steady state amplitude that remains constant during time, which is represented by a scalar.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Other sounds can have percussive amplitude envelopes featuring an abrupt onset followed by an immediate exponential decay.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Percussive amplitude envelopes are characteristic of various impact sounds: two wine glasses clinking together, hitting a drum, slamming a door, etc. where the amplitude is transient and must be represented as either a continuous function or a discrete vector.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Percussive amplitude envelopes model many common sounds that have a transient loudness attack, decay, sustain, and release.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] With waveforms containing many overtones, complex transient timbres can be achieved by assigning each overtone to its own distinct transient amplitude envelope.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] Unfortunately, this has the effect of modulating the loudness of the sound as well.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] It makes more sense to separate loudness and harmonic quality to be parameters controlled independently of each other.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] To do so, harmonic amplitude envelopes are frame-by-frame normalized to become amplitude *proportion* envelopes, where at each time frame all the harmonic amplitudes will add to 100% (or 1).
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] This way, the main loudness-controlling envelope can be cleanly controlled.
[src:battery-charger/amplitude] In Sound Recognition, max amplitude normalization can be used to help align the key harmonic features of 2 alike sounds, allowing similar timbres to be recognized independent of loudness.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] An **Automated Charging Machine** (**ACM**) is an electronic machine that provides the public with the ability to recharge a mobile device, often for a small fee.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] Similar to vending machines, ACMs take cash, then charge the connected devices, which may be cell phones, PDAs, or other handheld devices.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] Usually, these machines charge much faster than normal chargers would charge them; some provide a charge in as little as 10 minutes.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] Public charging stations for mobile devices appeared around 2006.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] A variety of features have been introduced to these machines, including lockers, UV sanitation, and wirelessly updated advertising space.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] Since the introduction of the idea, an increasing number of companies are looking toward ACMs for vending and advertising revenue.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] ACMs are generally deployed in areas with a high amount of foot traffic, similar to vending machines and ATMs.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] These places include airports, shopping malls, parks, clubs, supermarkets, campuses, and other popular locations.
[src:battery-charger/automated-charging-machine] Though is it unknown how many ACMs are in use around the world, they can be found in a variety of countries including the United States, England, and China.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Such items include mobile phone chargers, cooling fans, portable fridges, electric air pumps, and power inverters.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In most vehicles, at least one car outlet is present.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Some vehicles may have more power outlets: usually one for the front passengers, one for the rear passengers and one for the luggage trunk.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The voltage of the power outlet is usually near 12 V DC, and may be elevated between 13.5 V to 15 V while the engine is running.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] On trucks, the voltage of the power outlet may be near 24 V DC.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The 12 V power circuit is protected by a car fuse, often rated at 10 to 20 amperes, which provides 120 to 240 watts of power.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Large appliances such as hair dryers or toasters draw too much power to be fed from an auxiliary power socket.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] If wired directly rather than through the ignition, an empty car battery can be charged through the outlet from an external power source, which is more convenient albeit slower than currents supported through electrical clamps on the car battery.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Many modern vehicles no longer have the auxiliary power outlet, with it being replaced by USB 2.0 or USB-C ports.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The electrical cigar-lighter was invented and patented in the early 1880s by the Swiss-Austrian inventor Friedrich Wilhelm Schindler.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In the 1890s, these tools were sold as electrical cigar lighters (*Cigarrenanzünder*, later *Zigarrenanzünder*) in the major German warehouse catalogues.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Before the Great Depression, cigarettes overtook cigars in sales, and they became more popularly known as "cigarette lighters", though they have remained the diameter of a standard cigar of 21 millimetres (0.83 in), or a 52 ring gauge.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In 1921, the Morris U.S. patent 1,376,154 was issued for a so-called "wireless" or "cordless" lighter with a removable element.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The igniter was heated in the socket and then manually removed for use after an appropriate time interval.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In the United States, cigarette lighters started appearing in 1925–1926 in some models.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] They were a standard feature by the 1950s.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In 1928, the Connecticut Automotive Specialty Company (Casco) in Bridgeport patented its version of an automotive cigarette lighter, which used a cord and reel.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In the reel-type lighters, the igniter unit was connected with a source of current by a cable that was wound on a spring drum so that the igniter unit and cable could be withdrawn from the socket and be used for lighting a cigar or cigarette.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] As the removable plug was returned to the socket, the wires were reeled back into it.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The circuit was closed either by pressing a button or removing the igniter from its socket.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The modern "automatic" removable automotive V-Coil lighter was developed by Casco in 1956, for which it received U.S. patent 2,959,664, issued in 1960.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The sockets and mating plugs are defined in the ANSI/SAE J563 specification.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] For the 12-volt systems, the center contact is the positive terminal and the shell is the negative terminal.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Most automobiles connect the negative terminal to the frame of the vehicle (negative ground).
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] 12-volt auto connectors are made to comply with a standard by Underwriters Laboratories for safety.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] UL2089 was developed to cover the requirements for portable adapters rated 24 V DC or less that are intended to be supplied from the battery-powered electrical system of a vehicle.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Products covered by the standard include cord assemblies of a plug that mates with the standard cigarette receptacle found in automobiles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Most often used in European automobiles, and sometimes as a second socket in American automobiles expressly for DC power connections.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Plugs often include a pilot light LED indicator to indicate that electrical power is connected.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Optionally, the plug may be equipped with an internal fuse for electrical safety, usually rated at 10 amps or less.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In some designs, the tip of the plug may be unscrewed to reveal a cylindrical glass fuse; other variants may use a blade-type fuse inserted into the side or back of the plug.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The lighter is a metal or plastic cylinder containing a thin flat coil of nichrome metal strip, through which high current (≈10 amperes) passes when the device is activated, usually by pushing it into the socket as though it were a push-button.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] When pushed in, the lighter is held against the force of a spring by a clip attached to a bimetallic strip.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The heating element glows orange hot in seconds, causing the bimetallic strip to bend and release the mechanism.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The handle pops out, eliminating the need for the user to time the heating operation.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] If the lighter is then promptly removed from its socket, it can light a cigarette, cigar, or tinder.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] A common feature of Italian cars in the 1960s to the 1970s, such as Alfa Romeos and Ferraris, is the Brico Pram cigarette lighter, which differs from conventional designs in that the lighter does not pop out for removal to light a cigarette, even though it visually resembles the traditional design.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The advantage of such a design is in safety as the red-hot heating element cannot be accidentally dropped onto an occupant's lap.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Still, it takes away the ability for the lighter to be removed for the receptacle to be used as a power outlet, and it also does not allow cigars to be lit as the opening is not large enough.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In newer cars, the socket is equipped with a plastic cover without the lighter heating element.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] However, the socket has been repurposed and continues to be used to power consumer electronics in vehicles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Often, a vehicle may come with several outlets for convenience, some in the rear passenger area of the vehicle or the cargo area, for powering portable devices.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] These outlets usually have a plastic cap tethered to them, and are usually labeled as being only for DC power, because they are not intended to withstand the heat produced by an electrical cigarette lighter.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The use of cigarette lighter receptacles to supply 12 volt DC power is an example of backward compatibility to a de facto standard.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] As a power connector, the lighter receptacle is larger, harder to use and less reliable than other DC connectors.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] There are two prong threaded plugs to stop the plug from falling out due to vibrations.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Cigarette lighter receptacles are in widespread use in many highway vehicles and some boats.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Portable cigarette lighter receptacles attached to cables and alligator clips for connection directly to car batteries are available for temporary use.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In newer vehicles, one or more USB connectors may also be provided.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Plus in newer cars, the power output from the lighter plug is so reliable that it can charge laptops, without any voltage problems.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Standardized 12 volt DC automobile plugs are defined in the United States by UL Standard 2089 regarding vehicle battery adapters.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] This standard covers plugs and cord sets that insert into cigarette lighter receptacles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In Europe, 12 volt plugs and sockets are not specially regulated and do not require approvals for the CE mark.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The male plug is sometimes used to feed power *into* a vehicle to recharge its battery because it usually has no regulatory circuitry between the outlet and the car battery.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] For instance, portable solar battery maintainers generally connect to a vehicle's battery in this manner.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Trickle chargers also sometimes connect in this way, eliminating the need to leave a vehicle's hood open, as well as eliminating the possibility of reversed polarity.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Most cars nowadays are designed with a battery-negative earthing system and therefore have a +12V positive power distribution.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In such a case, the centre pin of a plug/socket will be +12V DC and the outer casing 0V.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] While polarity is not an issue for a cigarette lighter, it is prudent to verify the correct matching of polarities when connecting other kinds of accessories.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Since the cigarette lighter socket was originally designed only to heat a cigarette lighter, repurposing these sockets as generic power connectors can lead to many problems.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] In addition to the issues with partially-compatible physical dimensions, the plugs can vibrate out of the socket under normal driving conditions, owing to poor retention.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Also, there have been reports of melted plug tips due to poor contact and heat generation from ohmic resistance.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] A second problem is that nominally "twelve-volt" power in cars fluctuates widely.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The outlet is connected directly to the electrical system of the car.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] When used, DC to DC converters will usually compensate for small fluctuations, but reliable power may not be available without an independent battery-powered uninterruptible power supply.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Rarely, more extreme cases of voltage fluctuation can occur when the car battery is disconnected while the engine is running, or when the car receives a jump start.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] The load dump transient may also ruin the diodes in the alternator by exceeding their breakdown voltage.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] A car receiving a jump start from a truck may be subject to a 24 V electrical system used in some vehicles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Also, a "double battery jump-start" is performed by some tow truck drivers in cold climates.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Equipment intended to be powered by the receptacle needs to account for intermittent contact, and voltages outside the nominal 12 V DC, such as maximum voltage 9–16 V continuously, or maximum voltage of 20 V lasting 1 hour, 24 V lasting 1 minute, and 40 V lasting 400 ms.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] An example of protection component ratings tolerance is +50 to −60 V DC.
[src:battery-charger/automobile-auxiliary-power-outlet] Robust equipment must tolerate temperatures varying between −40 and +85 °C (−40 and 185 °F), plus possible high humidity and condensation of water.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:battery-charger/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:battery-charger/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A **battery charger**, **recharger**, or simply **charger**, is a device that stores energy in an electric battery by running current through it.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The charging protocol—how much voltage and current, for how long and what to do when charging is complete—depends on the size and type of the battery being charged.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some battery types have high tolerance for overcharging after the battery has been fully charged and can be recharged by connection to a constant voltage source or a constant current source, depending on battery type.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Simple chargers of this type must be manually disconnected at the end of the charge cycle.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Other battery types use a timer to cut off when charging should be complete.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Other battery types cannot withstand over-charging, becoming damaged (reduced capacity, reduced lifetime), over heating or even exploding.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The charger may have temperature or voltage sensing circuits and a microprocessor controller to safely adjust the charging current and voltage, determine the state of charge, and cut off at the end of charge.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Chargers may elevate the output voltage proportionally with current to compensate for impedance in the wires.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A trickle charger provides a relatively small amount of current, only enough to counteract self-discharge of a battery that is idle for a long time.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some battery types cannot tolerate trickle charging; attempts to do so may result in damage.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Lithium-ion batteries cannot handle indefinite trickle charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Slow battery chargers may take several hours to complete a charge.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] High-rate chargers may restore most capacity much faster, but high-rate chargers can be more than some battery types can tolerate.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Such batteries require active monitoring of the battery to protect it from any abusive use.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Electric vehicles ideally need high-rate chargers.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] For public access, installation of such chargers and the distribution support for them is an issue in the proposed adoption of electric cars.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Charge and discharge rates are often given as *C* or *C-rate*, which is a measure of the rate at which a battery is charged or discharged relative to its capacity.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The C-rate is defined as the charge or discharge current divided by the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] While rarely stated explicitly, the unit of the C-rate is h−1, equivalent to stating the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge in unit hour times current in the same unit as the charge or discharge current.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The C-rate is never negative, so whether it describes a charging or discharging process depends on the context.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] For example, for a battery with a capacity of 500 mAh, a discharge rate of 5000 mA (i.e., 5 A) corresponds to a C-rate of 10C, meaning that such a current can discharge 10 such batteries in one hour.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Likewise, for the same battery a charge current of 250 mA corresponds to a C-rate of C/2, meaning that this current will increase the state of charge of this battery by 50% in one hour.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Running current through batteries generates internal heat, roughly proportional to the current involved (a battery's current state of charge, condition / history, etc. are also factors).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] If the charging process is endothermic (which is the case for Ni–Cd batteries, whereas charging nickel–metal hydride batteries is exothermic) the charging process initially cools the battery, but as it reaches full charge, the cooling effect stops and the cell heats up.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Detecting a temperature rise of 10 °C (18 °F) is one way of determining when to stop charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Battery cells which have been built to allow higher C-rates than usual must make provision for increased heating.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] But high C-ratings are attractive to end users because such batteries can be charged more quickly, and produce higher current output in use.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] High C-rates typically require the charger to carefully monitor battery parameters such as terminal voltage and temperature to prevent overcharging and so damage to the cells.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Such high-charging rates are possible only with some battery types.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Others will be damaged or possibly overheat or catch fire.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] For example, an automobile SLI (starting, lighting, ignition) lead–acid battery carries several risks of explosion.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A simple charger works by supplying a constant DC or pulsed DC power source to a battery being charged.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A simple charger typically does not alter its output based on charging time or the charge on the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] This simplicity means that a simple charger is inexpensive, but there are tradeoffs.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Typically, a carefully designed simple charger takes longer to charge a battery because it is set to use a lower (i.e., safer) charging rate.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Even so, many batteries left on a simple charger for too long will be weakened or destroyed due to over-charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These chargers also vary in that they can supply either a constant voltage or a constant current, to the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Simple AC-powered battery chargers usually have much higher ripple current and ripple voltage than other kinds of battery chargers because they are inexpensively designed and built.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Generally, when the ripple current is within a battery's manufacturer recommended level, the ripple voltage will also be well within the recommended level.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The maximum ripple current for a typical 12 V 100 Ah VRLA battery is 5 amperes.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] As long as the ripple current is not excessive (more than 3 to 4 times the level recommended by the battery manufacturer), the expected life of a ripple-charged VRLA battery will be within 3% of the life of a constant DC-charged battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Fast chargers make use of control circuitry to rapidly charge the batteries without damaging any of the cells in the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The control circuitry can be built into the battery (generally for each cell) or in the external charging unit, or split between both.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Most such chargers have a cooling fan to help keep the temperature of the cells at safe levels.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Most fast chargers are also capable of acting as standard overnight chargers if used with standard Ni–MH cells that do not have the special control circuitry.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] To accelerate the charging time and provide continuous charging, an intelligent charger attempts to detect the state of charge and condition of the battery and applies a three-stage charging scheme.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The following description assumes a sealed lead–acid traction battery at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The first stage is referred to as "bulk absorption"; the charging current is held high and constant and is limited by the capacity of the charger.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] When the voltage on the battery reaches its outgassing voltage (2.22 volts per cell) the charger switches to the second stage, and the voltage is held constant (2.40 volts per cell).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The delivered current declines at the maintained voltage, and when the current reaches less than 0.005C the charger enters its third stage and the charger output is held constant at 2.25 volts per cell.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] In the third stage, the charging current is very small, 0.005C, and at this voltage the battery can be maintained at full charge and compensate for self-discharge.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers use electromagnetic induction to charge batteries.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A charging station sends electromagnetic energy through inductive coupling to an electrical device, which stores the energy in the batteries.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] This is achieved without the need for metal contacts between the charger and the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers are commonly used in electric toothbrushes and other devices used in bathrooms.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Because there are no open electrical contacts, there is no risk of electrocution.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Nowadays it is being used to charge wireless phones.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A smart charger can respond to the condition of a battery and modify its charging parameters accordingly, whereas "dumb" chargers apply a steady voltage, possibly through a fixed resistance.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] It should not be confused with a smart battery that contains a computer chip and communicates digitally with a smart charger about battery condition.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A smart battery requires a smart charger.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some smart chargers can also charge "dumb" batteries, which lack any internal electronics.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The output current of a smart charger depends upon the battery's state.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] An intelligent charger may monitor the battery's voltage, temperature or charge time to determine the optimum charge current or terminate charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] For Ni–Cd and Ni–MH batteries, the voltage of the battery increases slowly during the charging process, until the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] After that, the voltage *decreases* because of increasing temperature, which indicates to an intelligent charger that the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Such chargers are often labeled as a ΔV, "delta-V", or sometimes "delta peak" charger, indicating that they monitor voltage change.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] This can cause even an intelligent charger not to sense that the batteries are already fully charged, and continue charging, the result of which may be overcharging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Many intelligent chargers employ a variety of cut-off systems to prevent overcharging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A typical smart charger fast-charges a battery up to about 85% of its maximum capacity in less than an hour, then switches to trickle charging, which takes several hours to top off the battery to its full capacity.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Several companies have begun making devices that charge batteries using energy from human motion, such as walking.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] An example, made by Tremont Electric, consists of a magnet held between two springs that can charge a battery as the device is moved up and down.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Such products have not yet achieved significant commercial success.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A pedal-powered charger for mobile phones fitted into desks has been created for installation in public spaces, such as airports, railway stations and universities.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] They have been installed in a number of countries on several continents.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some chargers use *pulse technology*, in which a series of electrical pulses is fed to the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The DC pulses have a strictly controlled rise time, pulse width, pulse repetition rate (frequency) and amplitude.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] This technology works with any size and type of battery, including automotive and valve-regulated ones.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] With pulse charging, high instantaneous voltages are applied without overheating the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] In a lead–acid battery, this breaks down lead-sulfate crystals, thus greatly extending the battery service life.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Several kinds of pulse chargers are patented, while others are open source hardware.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some chargers use pulses to check the current battery state when the charger is first connected, then use constant current charging during fast charge, then use pulse mode to trickle charge it.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some chargers use "negative pulse charging", also called "reflex charging" or "burp charging".
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These chargers use both positive and brief negative current pulses.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] There is no significant evidence that negative pulse charging is more effective than ordinary pulse charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Solar chargers convert light energy into low-voltage DC current.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] They are generally portable, but can also be fixed mounted.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Fixed mount solar chargers are also known as solar panels.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These are often connected to the electrical grid via control and interface circuits, whereas portable solar chargers are used off-grid (i.e. cars, boats, or RVs).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Although portable solar chargers obtain energy only from the sun, they can charge in low light like at sunset.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Portable solar chargers are often used for trickle charging, though some can completely recharge batteries.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The output of a timer charger is terminated after a predetermined time interval.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Timer chargers were the most common type for high-capacity Ni–Cd cells in the late 1990s to charge low-capacity consumer Ni–Cd cells.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Often a timer charger and set of batteries could be bought as a bundle and the charger time is set for those batteries specifically.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] If batteries of lower capacity are charged, then they would be overcharged, and if batteries of higher capacity were timer-charged, they would not reach full capacity.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Timer based chargers also had the drawback that charging batteries that were not fully discharged would result in over-charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A trickle charger is typically low-current (usually between 5–1,500 mA).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] They are generally used to charge small capacity batteries (2–30 Ah).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] They are also used to maintain larger capacity batteries (> 30 Ah) in cars and boats.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] In larger applications, the current of the battery charger is only sufficient to provide trickle current.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Depending on the technology of the trickle charger, it can be left connected to the battery indefinitely.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some battery types are not suitable for trickle charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] For instance, most Li-ion batteries cannot be safely trickle charged and can cause a fire or explosion.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Charge DC (battery) from DC source without conversion to AC.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Modern DC-DC chargers often include isolator and DC-DC converter.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some may also have BMS (including balance), be bidirectional (jump start primary car battery from secondary battery) and wireless control (Bluetooth, WiFi, NFC, 5G).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The most sophisticated chargers are used in critical applications (e.g. military or aviation batteries).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These heavy-duty automatic "intelligent charging" systems can be programmed with complex charging cycles specified by the battery manufacturer.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The best are universal (i.e. can charge all battery types), and include automatic capacity testing and analyzing functions.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Since the Universal Serial Bus specification provides five-volt power, it is possible to use a USB cable to connect a device to a power supply.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Products based on this approach include chargers for cellular phones, portable digital audio players, and tablet computers.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] They may be fully compliant USB peripheral devices or uncontrolled, simple chargers.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Another type of USB charger called "USB (rechargeable) battery" is fitted into the case of standard batteries (1.5 V AA, C, D, and 9 V block) together with a Li-ion rechargeable battery, voltage converter, and USB connector.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Since a battery charger is intended to be connected to a battery, it may not have voltage regulation or filtering of the DC voltage output; it is cheaper to make them that way.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Battery chargers equipped with both voltage regulation and filtering are sometimes termed battery eliminators.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Chargers for car batteries come in varying ratings.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Chargers that are rated up to two amperes may be used to maintain charge on parked vehicle batteries or for small batteries on garden tractors or similar equipment.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A motorist may keep a charger rated a few amperes to ten or fifteen amperes for maintenance of automobile batteries or to recharge a vehicle battery that has accidentally discharged.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Service stations and commercial garages will have a large charger to fully charge a battery in an hour or two; often these chargers can briefly source the hundreds of amperes required to crank an internal combustion engine starter.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Electric vehicle battery chargers (ECS) come in a variety of brands and characteristics.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These chargers vary from 1 kW to 22 kW maximum charge rate.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some use algorithm charge curves, others use constant voltage, constant current.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some are programmable by the end user through a CAN port, some have dials for maximum voltage and amperage, some are preset to specified battery pack voltage, ampere-hour and chemistry.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A 10-ampere-hour battery could take 15 hours to reach a fully charged state from a fully discharged condition with a 1-ampere charger as it would require roughly 1.5 times the battery's capacity.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Public EV charging stations often provide 6 kW (host power of 208 to 240 V AC off a 40-ampere circuit).
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] 6 kW will recharge an EV roughly six times faster than 1 kW overnight charging.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Rapid charging results in even faster recharge times and is limited only by available AC power, battery type, and the type of charging system.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Power-factor correction (PFC) chargers can more closely approach the maximum current the plug can deliver, shortening charging time.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Project Better Place was deploying a network of charging stations and subsidizing vehicle battery costs through leases and credits until filing for bankruptcy in May 2013.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Most mobile phone chargers are not really chargers, only power adapters that provide a power source for the charging circuitry which is almost always contained within the mobile phone.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some higher-end models feature multiple ports which are equipped with a display which indicates output current.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Some support communication protocols for charging parameters such as Qualcomm Quick Charge or MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Chargers for 12 V automobile auxiliary power outlets may support input voltages of up to 24 or 32 V DC to ensure compatibility, and are sometimes equipped with a display to monitor current or the voltage of the vehicle's electrical system.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] China, the European Union, and other countries are making a national standard on mobile phone chargers using the USB standard.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] In June 2009, 10 of the world's largest mobile phone manufacturers signed a Memorandum of Understanding to develop specifications for and support a microUSB-equipped common external power supply (EPS) for all data-enabled mobile phones sold in the EU.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] On October 22, 2009, the International Telecommunication Union announced that microUSB would be the standard for a universal charger for mobile handsets.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] In October 2022 the EU's Common Charger Directive was approved with the new rules applying to mobile phones and a number of other devices, which came into force in December 2024.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Telecommunications, electric power, and computer uninterruptible power supply facilities may have very large standby battery banks (installed in battery rooms) to maintain critical loads for several hours during interruptions of primary grid power.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Such chargers are permanently installed and equipped with temperature compensation, supervisory alarms for various system faults, and often redundant independent power supplies and redundant rectifier systems.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Chargers for stationary battery plants may have adequate voltage regulation and filtration and sufficient current capacity to allow the battery to be disconnected for maintenance, while the charger supplies the direct current (DC) system load.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The capacity of the charger is specified to maintain the system load and recharge a completely discharged battery within, say, 8 hours or other intervals.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] A properly designed charger can allow batteries to reach their full cycle life.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Excess charging current, lengthy overcharging, or cell reversal in a multiple cell pack cause damage to cells and limit the life expectancy of a battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Most modern cell phones, laptop and tablet computers, and most electric vehicles use lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These batteries last longest if the battery is frequently charged; fully discharging the cells will degrade their capacity relatively quickly, but most such batteries are used in equipment which can sense the approach of full discharge and discontinue equipment use.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] When stored after charging, lithium battery cells degrade more while fully charged than if they are only 40–50% charged.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] As with all battery types, degradation also occurs faster at higher temperatures.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Degradation in lithium-ion batteries is caused by an increased internal battery resistance often due to the cell oxidation.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] This decreases the efficiency of the battery, resulting in less net current available to be drawn from the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] However, if Li-ion cells are discharged below a certain voltage a chemical reaction occurs that make them dangerous if recharged, which is why many such batteries in consumer goods now have an "electronic fuse" that permanently disables them if the voltage falls below a set level.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] The electronic fuse circuitry draws a small amount of current from the battery, which means that if a laptop battery is left for a long time without charging it, and with a very low initial state of charge, the battery may be permanently destroyed.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Motor vehicles, such as boats, RVs, ATVs, motorcycles, cars, trucks, etc. have used lead–acid batteries.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] These batteries employ a sulfuric acid electrolyte and can generally be charged and discharged without exhibiting memory effect, though sulfation (a chemical reaction in the battery which deposits a layer of sulfates on the lead) will occur over time.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Typically sulfated batteries are simply replaced with new batteries, and the old ones recycled.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Lead–acid batteries will experience substantially longer life when a maintenance charger is used to "float charge" the battery.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] This prevents the battery from ever being below 100% charge, preventing sulfate from forming.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Proper temperature compensated float voltage should be used to achieve the best results.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Battery charging technology is developing to support the increasing demands of electric vehicles (EVs), consumer electronics, and sustainable energy systems.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Modern chargers may feature Internet of things (IoT) connectivity for real-time monitoring, adaptive charging protocols, remote management, predictive maintenance, and may enhance safety and efficiency.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Artificial intelligence (AI) is being integrated into battery management systems to optimize charging rates, predict battery health, extend usable life, and maximize energy efficiency.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] As a result of electric mobility and smart device proliferation, the global battery charger market is projected (as of 2025) to see significant growth over the following decade.
[src:battery-charger/battery-charger] Smart chargers integrating IoT, AI, and adaptive features are expected to outpace traditional models globally.
